  <h3>Face-to-face support groups</h3>
  <p>Diabetes UK has regular meet-ups. <a href="https://www.diabetes.org.uk/how_we_help/local_support_groups">Find a Diabetes UK support group near you.</a></p>
  <p>It’s also worth asking your diabetes team if they know any local groups.</p>
  <h2>Diabetes helpline</h2>
  <p>Diabetes UK has a confidential helpline. Call if you need someone to talk to or you have questions about day-to-day management.</p>
  <div class="callout callout--info">
    <p>Call: 0345 123 2399</p>
    <p>Monday to Friday, 9am to 6pm</p>
    <p>Email: <a href="#">helpline@diabetes.org.uk</a></p>
  </div>
  <h2>Get talking therapies</h2>
  <p>If you’re feeling low and struggling to cope with your diabetes, a talking therapy might help.  A therapist won’t have experience of diabetes, but they can help you cope with a long-term condition. </p>
  <p>Ask your GP about talking therapies. They will know what’s available locally.</p>
